      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXVIII&mdash;THE ETERNAL CITY
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      In the night of the seven-hill&rsquo;d city, disrobed, and uncrown&rsquo;d,
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      and undone,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Thou moanest, O Rizpah, Madonna, and countest the hones of
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      thy son.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      The bier is vacant above thee, His corpse is no longer thereon,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      A wind came out of the dark, and he fell as a leaf, and is gone!
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      They have taken thy crown, O Rizpah, and driven thee forth
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      with the swine,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      But the bones of thy Son they have left thee&mdash;yea, wash them
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      with tears&mdash;they are thine!
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Thou moanest an old incantation, thou troublest earth with thy
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      cries....
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Ah, God, if the bones should hear thee, and join once again,
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      and arise!&mdash;<i>Home: a Poem.</i>
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">A</span>s the days passed,
      Bradley found his state of suspense and anxiety intolerable. Day after day
      he had hoped to hear from Alma, until at length disappointment culminated
      in despair.
    </p>
    <p>
      He then determined he should know with certainty what had become of her,
      and resolved to go to Milan.
    </p>
    <p>
      What he had seen at the <i>séance</i> had impressed him more than he would
      admit to himself. He could not believe that any evil had happened&mdash;he
      would not believe it without the most positive evidence of the fact. So he
      said to himself one hour, and the next his heart grew sick with an
      uncontrollable dread; and he refused to hope that the revelation of the <i>séance</i>
      was a delusion.
    </p>
    <p>
      He left his home and proceeded to the station in the former mood, but the
      train had hardly moved from the platform when his despair seized him, and
      if he could he would have relinquished the journey. Alternating thus
      between hope and despair, he travelled without a break, and in due course
      he reached Milan.
    </p>
    <p>
      His inquiries about Alma were promptly answered.
    </p>
    <p>
      The beautiful and wealthy English lady was well known. She had, until
      quite recently, been the occupant of a splendid suite of apartments in the
      best quarter of the city; but she had gone.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley heard all this, and almost savagely he repeated after his
      informant, an old Italian waiter who spoke English well, the word &lsquo;Gone!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Gone where?&rsquo; he demanded. &lsquo;You must know where she has gone to?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, Signor; she has gone to Rome!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;To Rome! And her address there is&mdash;&mdash;?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That I do not know, Signor.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Have me taken to the house she occupied when here,&rsquo; Bradley ordered; and
      he was driven to the house Alma had dwelt in.
    </p>
    <p>
      There also he failed to learn Alina&rsquo;s address. All that was known was that
      she had gone to Rome; that her departure had been sudden, and that she had
      said she would not return to Milan.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dismissing the carriage that had brought him, he walked back to his hotel.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was night; the cool breeze from the Alps was delightfully refreshing
      after the sultry heat of the day; the moon was full and the fair old city
      was looking its fairest, but these things Bradley heeded not. Outward
      beauty he could not see, for all his mind and soul was dark&mdash;the
      ancient palaces, the glorious Cathedral, the splendid Carrara marble
      statue of Leonardo, and the bronze one of Cavour, were passed unnoticed
      and uncared for. One thing only was in his mind&mdash;to get to Rome to
      find Alma. One thing was certain: she had left Milan in good health, and
      must surely be safe still.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ah!&rsquo; he said to himself, &lsquo;when did she leave Milan? Fool that I am, not
      to have learned,&rsquo; and, almost running, he returned to the house and
      inquired.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was disappointed with the information he received. Alma had left Milan
      some time before the <i>séance</i> in London had been held.
    </p>
    <p>
      Entering a restaurant, he found that he could get a train to Tome at
      midnight. He returned to his hotel, ate a morsel of food, drank some wine,
      and then went to the railway station.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was early morning when he entered the Eternal City, and the lack of
      stir upon the streets troubled and depressed him. It accentuated the
      difference between his present visit and the last he had made, and he
      cried in his heart most bitterly that the burden of his sorrow was too
      great.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was about to tell the driver of the fiacre to take him to his old
      quarters on the Piazza di Spagna, when he changed his mind. If he went
      there he would be in the midst of his countrymen, and in his then mood the
      last being he wished to see was an Englishman. So he asked the driver to
      take him to any quiet and good boarding-house he knew, and was taken to
      one in the Piazza Sta. Maria in Monti.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the course of the day he went out to learn what he could of Alma.
    </p>
    <p>
      He met several acquaintances, but they had neither seen nor heard of her;
      indeed, they were not in her circle, and though they had seen or heard of
      her, they would hardly have remembered. Bradley well knew the families
      Alma would be likely to visit, but he shrank from inquiring at their
      houses; he went to the doors of several and turned away without asking to
      be admitted.
    </p>
    <p>
      By-and-by he went into the Caffé Nuovo, and eagerly scanned the papers,
      but found no mention of Alma in them. A small knot of young Englishmen and
      Americans sat near to him, and he thought at last that he caught the name
      of Miss Craik mentioned in their conversation.
    </p>
    <p>
      He listened with painful attention, and found that they were speaking of
      some one the Jesuits had &lsquo;hooked,&rsquo; as they put it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And, by Jove, it was a haul!&rsquo; one young fellow said. &lsquo;Any amount of cash,
      I am told.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That is so,&rsquo; replied one of his comrades; and the girl is wonderfully
      beautiful, they say.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley started at this, and listened more intently than before.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes,&rsquo; the first speaker said, &lsquo;she is beautiful. I had her pointed out to
      me in Milan, and I thought her the best-looking woman I had ever seen.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Excuse me,&rsquo; said Bradley, stepping up to the speakers. &lsquo;I&mdash;I would
      like to know the name of the lady you refer to.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, certainly; her name is Miss Alma Craik.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Alma living!&rsquo; Bradley shrieked, and staggered, like one in drink, out of
      the caffé.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dazed and half maddened, he found his way to the lodging. He locked the
      door of his room and paced the floor, now clenching his hands together,
      then holding his forehead in them as if to still its bounding pain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Taken by the Jesuits!&rsquo; he muttered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then she is dead indeed&mdash;ay, worse than dead!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He paused at length at the window and looked out. The next instant he
      sprang back with a look of utter horror on his face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What if she is over <i>there!</i>&rsquo; he gasped, and sank into a chair.
    </p>
    <p>
      By over there he meant the convent of the Farnesiani nus. From the window
      he could see down the <i>cul-de-sac</i> that led to the convent. He knew
      the place well; he knew it to be well deserving of its name, the Living
      Tomb, and that of its inmates it was said &lsquo;they daily die and dig their
      own graves.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      If Alma was indeed in there, then she was lost.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley shook off as far as he could his feeling of helplessness and
      hopelessness, and with frenzied haste he rose from the chair, left the
      house, and went over towards the convent.
    </p>
    <p>
      He knew that the only way to communicate with the inmates was to mount to
      a platform above the walls of the houses, and to rap on a barrel
      projecting from the platform. He had once been there and had been
      admitted. He forgot that then he had proper credentials, and that now he
      had none.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was soon on the platform, and not only rapped, but thundered on the
      barrel.
    </p>
    <p>
      A muffled voice from the interior demanded his business.
    </p>
    <p>
      His reply was whether an Englishwoman named Craik was within the convent.
      To that question he had no answer, and the voice within did not speak
      again.
    </p>
    <p>
      He stayed long and repeated his question again and again in the hope of
      obtaining an answer, and only left when he had attracted attention, and
      was invited by the police to desist.
    </p>
    <p>
      What was to be done? he asked himself as he stood in the street. Do
      something he must, but what?
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I have it!&rsquo; he said. &lsquo;I will go to the Jesuit head-quarters and demand to
      be informed;&rsquo; and putting his resolve into action he walked thither.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was courteously received, and asked his business.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My business is a painful one,&rsquo; Bradley began. &lsquo;I wish to know if an
      English lady named Craik has joined your church?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She did return to the true faith,&rsquo; replied the priest, raising his eyes
      to heaven, &lsquo;and for her return the Holy Virgin and the Saints be praised!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And <i>now</i>&mdash;where is she <i>now?</i>&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      With painful expectancy he waited for the priest to answer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Now! now, Signor, she is <i>dead!</i>&rsquo; was the reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley heard, and fell prone upon the floor.
    </p>
    <p>
      On recovering from his swoon, Bradley found himself surrounded by several
      priests, one of whom was sprinkling his face with water, while another was
      beating the palms of his hands. Pale and trembling, he struggled to his
      feet, and gazed wildly around him, until his eyes fell upon the face of
      the aged official whom he had just accosted. He endeavoured to question
      him again, but the little Italian at his command seemed to have forsaken
      him, and he stammered and gasped in a kind of stupefaction.
    </p>
    <p>
      At this moment he heard a voice accost him in excellent English; a softly
      musical voice, full of beautiful vibrations.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I am sorry, sir, at your indisposition. If you will permit me, I will
      conduct you back to your hotel.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The speaker, like his companions, had the clean-shaven face of a priest,
      but his expression was bright and good-humoured. His eyebrows were black
      and prominent, but his hair was white as snow.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley clutched him by the arm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What&mdash;what does it mean? I must have been dreaming. I came here to
      inquire after a dear friend&mdash;a lady; and that man told me&mdash;told
      me&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Pray calm yourself,&rsquo; said the stranger gently. &lsquo;First let me take you
      home, and then I myself will give you whatever information you desire.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No!&rsquo; cried Bradley, &lsquo;I will have the truth <i>now!</i>&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      And as he faced the group of priests his eyes flashed and his hands were
      clenched convulsively. To his distracted gaze they seemed like evil
      spirits congregated for his torture and torment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What is it you desire to know?&rsquo; demanded he who had spoken in English. As
      he spoke he glanced quietly at his companions, with a significant movement
      of the eyebrows; and, as if understanding the sign, they withdrew from the
      apartment, leaving himself and Bradley quite alone.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Pray sit down,&rsquo; he continued gently, before Bradley could answer his
      former question.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the other paid no attention to the request.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Do not trifle with me,&rsquo; he cried, &lsquo;but tell me at once what I demand to
      know. I have been to the convent, seeking one who is said to have recently
      joined your church&mdash;which God forbid! When I mentioned her name I
      received no answer; but it is common gossip that a lady bearing her name
      was recently taken there. You can tell me if this is true.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The priest looked at him steadfastly, and, as it seemed, very sadly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Will you tell me the lady&rsquo;s name?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She is known as Miss Alma Craik, but she has a right to another name,
      which she shall bear.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Alas!&rsquo; said the other, with a deep sigh and a look full of infinite
      compassion, &lsquo;I knew the poor lady well. Perhaps, if you have been in
      correspondence with her, she mentioned my name&mdash;the Abbé Brest?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Never,&rsquo; exclaimed Bradley.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What is it you wish to know concerning her? I will help you as well as I
      can.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;First, I wish to be assured that that man lied (though of course I <i>know</i>
      he lied) when he said that evil had happened to her, that&mdash;that she
      had died. Next, I demand to know where she is, that I may speak to her. Do
      not attempt to keep her from me! I <i>will</i> see her!&rsquo; The face of the
      Abbé seemed to harden, while his eyes retained their sad, steadfast gaze.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Pardon me,&rsquo; he said after a moment&rsquo;s reflection, &lsquo;and do not think that I
      put the question in rudeness or with any want of brotherly sympathy&mdash;but
      by what right do you, a stranger, solicit this information? If I give it
      you, I must be able to justify myself before my superiors. The lady, or,
      as I should rather say, our poor Sister, is, as I understand, in no way
      related to you by blood?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She is my <i>wife!</i>&rsquo; answered Bradley.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was now the other&rsquo;s turn to express, or at least assume, astonishment.
      Uttering an incredulous exclamation, he raised his eyes to heaven, and
      slightly elevated his hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Do you think I lie?&rsquo; cried Bradley sternly. &lsquo;Do you think I lie, like
      those of your church, whose trade it is to do so? I tell you I have come
      here to claim her who is my wife, by the laws of man and God!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Again the Abbé repeated his pantomime expressive of pitiful incredulity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Surely you deceive yourself,&rsquo; he said. &lsquo;Miss Craik was never married. She
      lived unmated, and in blessed virginity was baptised into our church.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Where is she? Let me speak to her!&rsquo; cried Bradley, with a sudden access
      of his old passion.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Abbé pointed upward.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She is with the saints of heaven!&rsquo; he said, and crossed himself.
    </p>
    <p>
      Again the unfortunate clergyman&rsquo;s head went round, and again he seemed
      about to fall; but recovering himself with a shuddering effort, he
      clutched the priest by the arm, exclaiming&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Torture me no more! You are juggling with my life, as you have done with
      hers. But tell me it is all false, and I will forgive you. Though you are
      a priest, you have at least the heart of a man. Have pity! If what you
      have said is true, I am destroyed body and soul&mdash;yes, body and soul!
      Have mercy upon me! Tell me my darling is not dead!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The Abbe&rsquo;s face went white as death, and at the same moment his lustrous
      eyes seemed to fill with tears. Trembling violently, he took Bradley&rsquo;s
      hand, and pressed it tenderly. Then releasing him, he glanced upward and
      turned towards the door of the chamber.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Stay here till I return,&rsquo; he said in a low voice, and disappeared.
    </p>
    <p>
      Half swooning, Bradley sank into a chair, covering his face with his
      hands. A quarter of an hour passed, and he still remained in the same
      position. Tears streamed from his eyes, and from time to time he moaned
      aloud in complete despair. Suddenly he felt a touch upon his shoulder, and
      looking up he again encountered the compassionate eyes of the Abbé Brest.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Come with me!&rsquo; the Abbé said.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley was too lost in his own wild fears and horrible conjectures to
      take any particular note of the manner of the priest. Had he done so, he
      would have perceived that it betrayed no little hesitation and agitation.
      But he rose eagerly, though as it were mechanically, and followed the Abbé
      to the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      A minute afterwards they were walking side by side in the open sunshine.
    </p>
    <p>
      To the bewildered mind of Ambrose Bradley it all seemed like a dream. The
      sunlight dazzled his brain so that his eyes could scarcely see, and he was
      only conscious of hurrying along through a crowd of living ghosts.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly he stopped, tottering.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What is the matter?&rsquo; cried the Abbé, supporting him. &lsquo;You are ill again,
      I fear; let me call a carriage.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      And, suiting the action to the word, he beckoned up a carriage which was
      just then passing. By this time Bradley had recovered from his momentary
      faintness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Where are you taking me?&rsquo; he demanded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Get in, and I will tell you!&rsquo; returned the other; and when Bradley had
      seated himself, he leant over to the driver and said something in a low
      voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley repeated his question, while the vehicle moved slowly away.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I am going to make inquiries,&rsquo; was the reply; &lsquo;and as an assurance of my
      sympathy and good faith, I have obtained permission for you to accompany
      me. But let me now conjure you to summon all your strength to bear the
      inevitable; and let it be your comfort if, as I believe and fear,
      something terrible has happened, to know that there is much in this world
      sadder far than death.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I ask you once more,&rsquo; said Bradley in a broken voice, &lsquo;where are you
      taking me?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;To those who can set your mind at rest, once and for ever.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who are they?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The Farnesiani sisters,&rsquo; returned the Abbé.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley sank back on his seat stupefied, with a sickening sense of horror.
    </p>
    <p>
      The mental strain and agony were growing almost too much for him to bear.
      Into that brief day he had concentrated the torture of a lifetime; and
      never before had he known with what utterness of despairing passion he
      loved the woman whom he indeed held to be, in the sight of God, his wife.
      With frenzied self-reproach he blamed himself for all that had taken
      place. Had he never consented to an ignoble deception, never gone through
      the mockery of a marriage ceremony with Alma, they might still have been
      at peace together; legally separated for the time being, but spiritually
      joined for ever; pure and sacred for each other, and for all the world.
      But <i>now</i>&mdash;now it seemed that he had lost her, body and soul!
    </p>
    <p>
      The carriage presently halted, and Bradley saw at a glance that they were
      at the corner of the <i>cul-de-sac</i> leading to the convent. They
      alighted, and the Abbé paid the driver. A couple of minutes later they
      were standing on the platform above the walls of the houses.
    </p>
    <p>
      All around them the bright sunshine burnt golden over the quivering roofs
      of Rome, and the sleepy hum of the Eternal City rolled up to them like the
      murmur of a summer sea.
    </p>
    <p>
      There they stood like two black spots on the aerial brightness; and again
      Bradley fell into one of those waking trances which he had of late so
      frequently experienced, and which he had frequently compared, in his
      calmer moments, to the weird seizures of the young Prince, &lsquo;blue-eyed and
      fair of face,&rsquo; in the &lsquo;Princess.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He moved, looked, spoke as usual, showing no outward indication of his
      condition; but a mist was upon his mind, and nothing was real; he seemed
      rather a disembodied spirit than a man; the Abbe&rsquo;s voice strange and far
      off, though clear and distinct as a bell; and when the Abbé rapped on the
      barrel, as he himself had done so recently, the voice that answered the
      summons sounded like a voice from the very grave itself.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
