      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXX&mdash;IN PARIS
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      Lay a garland on my hearse,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Of the dismal yew;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Maidens, willow gardens bear;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Say I died true.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      My love was false, but I was firm
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      From my hour of birth;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Upon my buried body lie
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Lightly, gentle earth.&mdash;<i>The Maid&rsquo;s Tragedy</i>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">P</span>rofessor
      Mapleleafe speedily saw that to oppose his sister would be inopportune&mdash;might
      perhaps even cause her decline and death. He determined&rsquo; therefore to
      humour her, and to delay for a short time their proposed return to
      America.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Look here, Eustasia,&rsquo; he said to her one day, &lsquo;I find I&rsquo;ve got something
      to do in Paris; you shall come with me. Perhaps the change there may bring
      you back to your old self again. Anyhow we&rsquo;ll try it; for if this goes on
      much longer you&rsquo;ll die!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No, Salem, I shan&rsquo;t die till I&rsquo;ve seen <i>him</i> again!&rsquo; she answered,
      with a faint forced smile.
    </p>
    <p>
      They set about making their preparations at once, and were soon on their
      way to Paris. The movement and change had given colour to Eustasia&rsquo;s
      cheeks, and brought a pleasurable light of excitement into her eyes, so
      that already her brother&rsquo;s spirits were raised.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She&rsquo;ll forget him,&rsquo; he said to himself, &lsquo;and we&rsquo;ll be what we were before
      he came!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      But in this Salem was mistaken. Eustasia was not likely to forget Bradley.
      Indeed, it was the thought of seeing him again that seemed to give new
      life to her rapidly wasting frame. She knew that he had left England; she
      thought that, like herself, he might be travelling to get rid of his own
      distracting thoughts; so wherever she went she looked about her to try and
      catch a glimpse of his face.
    </p>
    <p>
      They fixed themselves in Paris, and Salem soon dropped into the old life.
      He fell amongst some kindred spirits, and the <i>séances</i> began again;
      Eustasia taking part in them to please her brother, but no more. She was
      utterly changed; each day as it rolled away seemed to take with it a part
      of her life, until her wasted frame became almost as etherealised as those
      of the spirits with whom she had dealt so much.
    </p>
    <p>
      With constant nursing and brooding upon, her fascination for the
      Englishman increased; it seemed, indeed, to be the one thing which kept
      her thin thread of life from finally breaking.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;If I could see him again,&rsquo; she murmured to herself, &lsquo;only once again, and
      then (as Salem says) die!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The wish of her heart was destined to be realised: she did at least see
      Bradley once again.
    </p>
    <p>
      She was sitting at home one day alone, when the door of the room opened,
      and more like a spectre than a man he walked in.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the first glimpse of his face Eustasia uttered a wild cry and staggered
      a few steps forward, as if about to throw herself into his arms; but
      suddenly she controlled herself, and sank half swooning into a chair.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You have come!&rsquo; she said at length, raising her eyes wistfully to his;
      &lsquo;you have come at last!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He did not answer, but kept his eyes fixed upon hers with a look which
      made her shudder.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;How&mdash;how did you find me?&rsquo; she asked faintly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I came to Paris, and by accident I heard of you,&rsquo; he answered in a hollow
      voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      Again there was silence. Bradley kept his eyes fixed upon the sibyl with a
      look which thrilled her to the soul. There was something about him which
      she could not understand; something which made her fear him. Looking at
      him more closely, she saw that he was curiously changed; his eyes were
      sunken and hollow; and though they were fixed upon her they seemed to be
      looking at something far away; his hair, too, had turned quite grey.
    </p>
    <p>
      She rose from her seat, approached him, and gently laid her hand upon his
      arm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mr. Bradley,&rsquo; she said, &lsquo;what is it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He passed his hand across his brow as if to dispel a dream, and looked at
      her curiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Eustasia,&rsquo; he said, using for the first time her Christian name, &lsquo;speak
      the truth to me to-day; tell me, is all this real?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Is what real?&rsquo; she asked, trembling. His presence made her faint, and the
      sound of her name, as he had spoken it, rang continually in her ears.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Is it not all a lie? Tell me that what you have done once you can do
      again; that you can bring me once more into the presence of the spirit of
      her I love!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Of her you love?&rsquo; said the girl, fixing her large eyes wistfully upon his
      face. &lsquo;What&mdash;what do you want me to do?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Prove that it is not all a lie and a cheat: if you are a true woman, as I
      trust, I want you to bring back to me the spirit of my darling who is
      dead!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She shrank for a moment from him, a sickening feeling of despair clouding
      all her senses; then she bowed her head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;When will you come?&rsquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;To-night.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Eustasia sank into her chair, and, without another word, Bradley departed.
    </p>
    <p>
      At seven o&rsquo;clock that night Bradley returned, and found the sibyl waiting
      for him.
    </p>
    <p>
      She was quite alone. Since the morning her manner had completely changed;
      her hands were trembling, her cheek was hushed, but there was a look of
      strange determination about her lips and in her eyes. Bradley shook hands
      with her, then looked around as if expecting others.
    </p>
    <p>
      She smiled curiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;We are to be alone!&rsquo; she said&mdash;&lsquo;quite alone. I thought it better for
      you!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      For some time she made no attempt to move; at length, noticing Bradley&rsquo;s
      impatience, she said quietly&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;We will begin.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She rose and placed herself opposite Bradley, and fixed her eyes intently
      upon him. Then, at her request, he turned down the gas; they were in
      almost total darkness touching hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      For some time after Bradley sat in a strange dream, scarcely conscious of
      anything that was taking place, and touching the outstretched hands of
      Eustasia with his own.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly a soft voice close to his ear murmured,&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ambrose, my love!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He started from his chair, and gazed wildly about him. He could see
      nothing, but he could feel something stirring close to him. Then he
      staggered back like a drunken man, and fell back in his chair.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Alma!&rsquo; he cried piteously, still conscious of the medium&rsquo;s trembling
      hands, &lsquo;Alma, my darling, come to me!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      For a moment there was silence, and Bradley could hear the beating of his
      heart. Then he became conscious of a soft hand upon his head; of lips that
      seemed to him like warm human lips pressed against his fore head.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gasping and trembling he cried&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Alma, speak; is it <i>you</i>?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The same soft voice answered him&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, it is I!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The hand passed again softly over his head and around his neck, and a pair
      of lips rich and warm were pressed passionately against his own. Half mad
      with excitement, Bradley threw one arm around the figure he felt to be
      near him, sprang to his feet while it struggled to disengage itself,
      turned up the light, and gazed full into the eyes of&mdash;Eustasia
      Mapleleafe.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Never till his dying day did Bradley forget the expression of the face
      which the sibyl now turned towards his own, while, half crouching, half
      struggling, she tried to free herself from the grip of his powerful arms;
      for though the cheeks were pale as death, the eyes wildly dilated, they
      expressed no terror&mdash;rather a mad and reckless desperation. The mask
      had quite fallen; any attempt at further disguise would have been sheer
      waste of force and time, and Eustasia stood revealed once and for all as a
      cunning and dangerous trickster, a serpent of miserable deceit.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yet she did not quail. She looked at the man boldly, and presently, seeing
      he continued to regard her steadfastly, as if lost in horrified wonder,
      she gave vent to her characteristic, scarcely audible, crooning laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      A thrill of horror went through him, as if he were under the spell of
      something diabolic.
    </p>
    <p>
      For a moment he felt impelled to seize her by the throat and strangle her,
      or to savagely dash her to the ground. Conquering the impulse, he held her
      still as in a vice, until at last he found a voice&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then you have lied to me? It has all been a lie from the beginning?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Let me go,&rsquo; she panted, &lsquo;and I will answer you!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Answer me <i>now</i>,&rsquo; he said between his set teeth.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the sibyl was not made of the sort of stuff to be conquered by
      intimidation. A fierce look came into her wonderful eyes, and her lips
      were closely compressed together.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Speak&mdash;or I may kill you! he cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Kill me, then!&rsquo; she answered. &lsquo;Guess I don t care!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      There was something in the wild face which mastered him in spite of
      himself. His hands relaxed, his arms sank useless at his side, and he
      uttered a deep despairing groan. Simultaneously she sprang to her feet,
      and stood looking down at him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Why did you break the conditions?&rsquo; she asked in a low voice. &lsquo;The spirits
      won&rsquo;t be trifled with in that way, and they&rsquo;ll never forgive you, or me;
      never.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He made no sign that he heard her, but stood moveless, his head sunk
      between his shoulders, his eyes fixed upon the ground. Struck by the
      sudden change in him, she moved towards him, and was about to touch him on
      the shoulder, when he rose, still white as death, and faced her once more.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Do not touch me!&rsquo; he cried. &lsquo;Do not touch me, and do not, if you have a
      vestige of goodness left within you, try to torture me again. But look me
      in the face, and answer me, if you can, truly, remembering it is the last
      time we shall ever meet. When you have told me the truth, I shall leave
      this place, never to return; shall leave <i>you</i>, never to look upon
      your face again. Tell me the truth, woman, and I will try to forgive you;
      it will be very hard, but I will try. I know I have been your dupe from
      the beginning, and that what I have seen and heard has been only a
      treacherous mirage called up by an adventuress and her accomplices. Is it
      not so? Speak! Let me have the truth from your own lips.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I can&rsquo;t tell,&rsquo; answered Eustasia coldly. &lsquo;If you mean that my brother and
      I have conspired to deceive you, it is a falsehood.
    </p>
    <p>
      We are simply agents in the hands of higher agencies than ours.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Once more, cease that jargon,&rsquo; cried Bradley; &lsquo;the time has long past for
      its use. Will you confess, before we part for ever? You will not? Then
      good-bye, and God forgive you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      So saying he moved towards the door; but with a sharp, bird-like cry she
      called him back.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Stay! you must not go!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He turned again towards her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then will you be honest with me? It is the last and only thing I shall
      ask of you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&mdash;I will try,&rsquo; she answered in a broken voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You will!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes; if you will listen to me patiently.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She sank into a chair, and covered her face with her hands. He stood
      watching her, and saw that her thin, white, trembling fingers were wet
      with tears.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Promise,&rsquo; she said, &lsquo;that what I am about to say to you shall never be
      told to any other living soul.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I promise.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Not even to my brother.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Not even to <i>him</i>.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      There was a long pause, during which he waited impatiently for her to
      continue. At last, conquering her agitation, she uncovered her face, and
      motioned to a chair opposite to her; he obeyed her almost mechanically,
      and sat down. She looked long and wistfully at him, and sighed several
      times as if in pain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Salem says I shan&rsquo;t live long,&rsquo; she murmured thoughtfully. &lsquo;To-night,
      more than ever, I felt like dying.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She paused and waited as if expecting him to speak, but he was silent.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Guess <i>you</i> don&rsquo;t care if I live or die?&rsquo; she added piteously, more
      like a sick child than a grown woman&mdash;and waited again.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I think I do care,&rsquo; he answered sadly, &lsquo;for in spite of all the anguish
      you have caused me, I am sorry for you. But I am not myself, not the man
      you once knew. All my soul is set upon one quest, and I care for nothing
      more in all the world. I used to believe there was a God; that there was a
      life after death; that if those who loved each other parted here, they
      might meet again elsewhere. In my despair and doubt, I thought that you
      could give me assurance and heavenly hope; and I clutched at the shadows
      you summoned up before me. I know now how unreal they were; I know now
      that you were playing tricks upon my miserable soul.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She listened to him, and when he ceased began to cry again.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I never meant any harm to <i>you</i>,&rsquo; she sobbed! &lsquo;I&mdash;I loved you
      too well.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You loved me!&rsquo; he echoed in amaze.
    </p>
    <p>
      She nodded quickly, glancing at him with her keen wild eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, Mr. Bradley. When Salem first took me to hear you preach, you seemed
      like the spirit of a man I once loved, and who once loved me. He&rsquo;s dead
      now, he is; died over there in the States, years ago. Well, afterwards,
      when I saw you again, I began to make believe to myself that you were that
      very man, and that he was living again in you. You think me crazy, don&rsquo;t
      you? Ah well, you&rsquo;ll think me crazier when you hear all the rest. I soon
      found out all about you; it wasn&rsquo;t very hard, and our people have ways of
      learning things you&rsquo;d never guess. I didn&rsquo;t look far till I found out your
      secret; that you loved another woman, I mean. That made me care for you
      all the more.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Her manner now was quite simple and matter-of-fact. Her face was quite
      tearless, and, with hands folded in her lap, she sat quietly looking into
      his face. He listened in sheer stupefaction. Until that moment no
      suspicion of the truth had ever flashed upon his mind. As Eustasia spoke,
      her features seemed to become elfin-like and old, with a set expression of
      dreary and incurable pain; but she made her avowal without the slightest
      indication of shame or self-reproach, though her manner, from time to
      time, was that of one pleading for sympathy and pity.
    </p>
    <p>
      She continued&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You don&rsquo;t understand me yet, and I guess you never will. I&rsquo;m not a
      European, and I haven&rsquo;t been brought up like other girls. I don&rsquo;t seem
      ever to have been quite young. I grew friends with the spirits when I
      wasn&rsquo;t old enough to understand, and they seem to have stolen my right
      heart away, and put another in its place.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Why do you speak of such things as if they were real? You know the whole
      thing is a trick and a lie.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No, I don&rsquo;t,&rsquo; she answered quickly. &lsquo;I&rsquo;m not denying that I&rsquo;ve played
      tricks with <i>them</i>, just as they&rsquo;ve played tricks with <i>me</i>; but
      they&rsquo;re downright real&mdash;they are indeed. First mother used to come to
      me, when I was very little; then others, and in after-days I saw <i>him</i>;
      yes, after he was dead. Then sometimes, when they wouldn&rsquo;t come, Salem
      helped out the manifestations, that&rsquo;s all.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For God&rsquo;s sake, be honest with me!&rsquo; cried Bradley. &lsquo;Confess that all
      these things are simple imposture. That photograph of yourself, for
      example&mdash;do you remember?&mdash;the picture your brother left in my
      room, and which faded away when I breathed upon it?&rsquo; She nodded her head
      again, and laughed strangely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It was a man out West that taught Salem how to do that,&rsquo; she replied
      naïvely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then it was a trick, as I suspected?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, I guess that was a trick. It was something they used in fixing the
      likeness, which made it grow invisible after it had been a certain time in
      contact with the atmospheric air.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Bradley uttered an impatient exclamation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And all the rest was of a piece with that! Well, I could have forgiven
      you everything but having personified one who is now lost to me for ever.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I never did. I suppose you <i>wished</i> to see her, and she came to you
      out of the spirit-land.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;<i>Now</i> you are lying to me again.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t you think I&rsquo;m lying,&rsquo; was the answer; &lsquo;for its gospel-truth I&rsquo;m
      telling you. I&rsquo;m not so bad as you think me, not half so bad.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Again shrinking from lier, lie looked at her with aimer and loathing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The device was exposed to-day,&rsquo; he said sternly. &lsquo;You spoke to me with
      her voice, and when I turned up the light I found that I was holding in my
      arms no spirit, but yourself.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, I&rsquo;m not denying that&rsquo;s true,&rsquo; she answered with another laugh.
      &lsquo;Something came over me&mdash;I don&rsquo;t know how it happened&mdash;and then,
      all at one, I was kissing you, and I had broken the conditions.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      By this time Bradley&rsquo;s brain had cleared, and he was better able to grasp
      the horrible reality of the situation. It was quite clear to him that the
      sibyl was either an utter impostor, or a person whose mental faculties
      were darkened by fitful clouds of insanity. What startled and horrified
      him most of all was the utter want of maidenly shame, the curious and
      weird sang-froid, with which she made her extraordinary confession. Her
      frankness, so far as it went, was something terrible&mdash;or, as the
      Scotch express it, &lsquo;uncanny.&rsquo; Across his recollection, as he looked and
      listened, came the thought of one of these mysterious sibyls, familiar to
      mediæval superstition, who come into the world with all the outward form
      and beauty of women, but without a Soul, but who might gain a spiritual
      existence in some mysterious way by absorbing the souls of men. The idea
      was a ghastly one, in harmony with his distempered fancy, and he could not
      shake it away.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Tell me,&rsquo; said Eustasia gently, &lsquo;tell me one thing, now I have told you
      so much. Is that poor lady dead indeed&mdash;I mean the lady you used to
      love?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The question went into his heart like a knife, and with livid face he rose
      to Ins feet.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Do not speak of her!&rsquo; he cried. &lsquo;I cannot bear it&mdash;it is blasphemy!
      Miserable woman, do you think that you will ever be forgiven for
      tampering, as you have done, with the terrible truth of death? I came to
      you in the last despairing hope that among all the phantoms you have
      conjured up before me there might be some reality; for I was blind and
      mad, and scarcely knew what I did. If it is any satisfaction to you, know
      that you have turned the world into a tomb for me, and destroyed my last
      faint ray of faith in a living God. In my misery, I clung to the thought
      of your spirit world; and I came to you for some fresh assurance that such
      a world might be. All that is over now. It is a cheat and a fraud like all
      the rest.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      With these words he left her, passing quickly from the room. Directly
      afterwards she heard the street door close behind him. Tottering to the
      window, she looked down in the street, and saw him stalk rapidly by, his
      white face set hard as granite, his eyes looking steadily before him,
      fixed on vacancy. As he disappeared, she uttered a low cry of pain, and
      placed her hand upon her heart.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
